name: railroader
description: A static analysis security vulnerability scanner for Ruby on Rails applications (OSS fork of Brakeman)
interact_justification: The website https://railroader.org explains how to obtain the software, and points to https://github.com/david-a-wheeler/railroader which describes the rest.
contribution_justification: Projects on GitHub by default use issues and pull requests, as encouraged by documentation such as <https://guides.github.com/activities/contributing-to-open-source/>.
contribution_requirements_justification: [CONTRIBUTING.md](https://github.com/david-a-wheeler/railroader/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md) documents contribution requirements.  These includes: Licensing (must be released under the MIT license at least), passes tests (`bundle exec rake`), passes style check (`bundle exec rubocop`), and signed commits.
license_location_justification: Non-trivial license location file in repository: <https://github.com/david-a-wheeler/railroader/blob/master/MIT-LICENSE>.
floss_license_justification: The MIT license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
floss_license_osi_justification: The MIT license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
documentation_basics_justification: Documentation provided.
repo_public_justification: Repository on GitHub, which provides public git repositories with URLs.
repo_track_justification: Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git can track the changes, who made them, and when they were made.
repo_distributed_justification: Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git is distributed.
report_tracker_justification: We use GitHub for tracking issues.
vulnerability_report_process_justificati: We publish the reporting process in our [CONTRIBUTING.md](https://github.com/david-a-wheeler/railroader/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md) file.  We specifically point to our reporting process from our [README.md](https://github.com/david-a-wheeler/railroader/blob/master/README.md) file, which is shown on the front page of the GitHub repo.
vulnerability_report_private_justificati: We encourage the use of StartTLS-encrypted email, as described in [CONTRIBUTING.md](https://github.com/david-a-wheeler/railroader/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md).
vulnerability_report_response_justificat: We've never received a vulnerability report.
build_floss_tools_justification: Built with Ruby.  Note: Ruby is a scripting languages, so it's not really "built" in the sense of a compiled language.
test_justification: We include an automated test suite.  It can be manually invoked using `bundle exec rake`, and it's also invoked through our continuous integration (CI) pipeline on every commit submitted to GitHub.
test_invocation_justification: `rake` is the usual way to invoke such checks.
test_most_justification: Our automated test suite covers over 90% of statements.
tests_are_added_justification: We haven't added major recent changes since we forked from Brakeman, but we modified the test suite so that the whole test suite now passes (it didn't before).
warnings_fixed_justification: We have fixed over 1,000 Rubocop reports since we forked from the Brakeman project.
warnings_strict_justification: We forked from a previous project (Brakeman) which didn't use any tool at all to create warnings.  Thus, as with all such changes, we can't just immediately be maximally strict with warnings.  Instead, we've enable rubocop at all, and are now slowly enabling specific warnings over time with the goal of *eventually* being maximally strict.  We just aren't there yet.
know_secure_design_justification: Lead developer (David A. Wheeler) literally wrote a book on how to develop secure software.
static_analysis_justification: We use Rubocop, a widely-used static code analysis tool for Ruby.
static_analysis_common_vulnerabilities_j: We don't know of any FLOSS tool that can work for our tech stack to find common vulnerabilities.  E.g., Rubocop doesn't have many rules to look for common vulnerabilities.  Since there isn't one, this is N/A.
static_analysis_fixed_justification: We've never had a vulnerability discovered since we started (as a fork from Brakeman).
static_analysis_often_justification: Every commit sent to GitHub is automatically checked by Rubocop.
dynamic_analysis_justification:
This criterion may be met, but since we aren't certain we're not claiming that it is met.

We use an automated test suite, and that suite has over 90% statement coverage.  However, we don't know its branch coverage, so we don't know if we've achieved it.
dynamic_analysis_unsafe_justification: The software is written in Ruby, which is memory-safe.
dynamic_analysis_fixed_justification: We've never had a vulnerability reported.
test_continuous_integration_justificatio: When a commit is sent to GitHub, we invoke a Travis build that invokes our automated tests and our static analysis tool (Rubocop).
discussion_justification: GitHub supports discussions on issues and pull requests.
hardened_site_justification: Found all required security hardening headers. // X-Content-Type-Options was not set to "nosniff".
installation_common_justification: We provide gems, which are the standard way to install and uninstall the software.
dco_justification: Commits must be signed-off-as as complying with the DCO, as described in https://github.com/david-a-wheeler/railroader/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md
sites_password_security_justification: The repository and download site is GitHub, which is known to meet this criterion.
maintenance_or_update_justification: We provide an upgrade path to newer versions.  The upgrade pate is trivial as long as the program uses Ruby 2.* (Ruby itself has not supported version 1.9 for years, and the Ruby developers separately describe how to do that upgrade).
vulnerability_report_credit_justificatio: We plan to credit all reporters unless they request anonymity.  However, there have been no vulnerabilities resolved ever.
coding_standards_enforced_justification: We use Rubocop to enforce our coding style.
build_standard_variables_justification: We do not generate native binaries.
build_preserve_debug_justification: We use rake and a Rakefile, which is a build system broadly construed, but because we use a scripting language we do not build separate executables.  We do build gems, but those are simply prepacked information including all the source code (including all debugging information).  The installation system (Ruby gems) doesn't strip out debugging information.
build_non_recursive_justification: We do not build a binary.
installation_standard_variables_justific: We build standard gem files, and support all standard conventions for where the gems may be installed.
installation_development_quick_justifica: We use standard Ruby conventions.  A `git clone` and `bundle install` gets you going.
external_dependencies_justification: We define our external dependencies in gem files.  The key file is https://github.com/david-a-wheeler/railroader/blob/master/gem_common.rb
updateable_reused_components_justificati: We use gem files to track externally-maintained components that are not provided by the system.  In particular, see: https://github.com/david-a-wheeler/railroader/blob/master/gem_common.rb
automated_integration_testing_justificat: Our CI configuration applies an automated test suite on each check-in.  See: https://github.com/david-a-wheeler/railroader/blob/master/.travis.yml
test_statement_coverage80_justification: Our automated test suite achieves over 90% statement coverage.
